<ArticleLayout
  title="Storage Under the Kitchen Sink"
  description="Check pipework, leaks, moisture, shelf clearance, cleaning-product sizes and bin space before choosing removable under-sink kitchen organisers."
  category="Kitchen"
  faqs={faqs}
  date="Updated July 2026"
  dateModified="2026-07-19"
  readingTime="6 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/kitchen.webp"
  imageAlt="A warm kitchen with tidy under-sink storage and practical cleaning supplies"
>
  <p>
    The cupboard beneath the sink looks like a box until the doors open. Pipes divide the back,
    hinges claim the sides, the bin needs room to lift out and every stored bottle makes the next
    leak harder to see.
  </p>
  <p>
    Empty and inspect the cabinet before adding shelves, drawers or caddies. The priority is
    access to plumbing and controlled storage for suitable products—not filling every gap.
  </p>
  <p>
    For the wider room plan, see{" "}
    <a href="/guides/best-kitchen-storage-ideas-small-australian-homes/">Kitchen Storage That Makes Small Cupboards Easier to Use</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Empty the cabinet and inspect the base</h2>
  <p>
    Remove everything, wipe the interior and look for damp, swelling, staining, corrosion, odour
    or an active drip. Check hoses, filters and valves without disturbing them. A liner or
    organiser must not hide a problem that needs repair.
  </p>
  <p>
    Deal with leaks and persistent moisture before reorganising. Storage can contain a small
    spill; it cannot fix plumbing or make a damp cabinet suitable for sensitive supplies.
  </p>

  <h2>Map the pipework in three dimensions</h2>
  <p>
    Measure usable width, depth and height in front of, beside and beneath each obstruction. Note
    traps, hoses, filters, valves and any fittings that need inspection or service access. A
    U-shaped shelf works only when its opening matches the real pipe position.
  </p>
  <p>
    Photograph the empty cabinet and record dimensions on the image. Product diagrams are easier
    to compare when the awkward sections are visible.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure the door opening and hinge sweep</h2>
  <p>
    The cabinet interior may be wider than the path through its doors. Measure the narrowest
    opening, centre stile and the space swept by hinges. Test a bin or caddy at the angle needed
    to remove it.
  </p>
  <p>
    Pull-out storage also needs a straight travel path and enough clearance for the handle. If a
    full drawer catches a hinge, it will become a fixed shelf with inaccessible contents behind
    it.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide what is appropriate to store there</h2>
  <p>
    The location may suit a modest group of dishwashing and cleaning supplies, bin liners,
    brushes or a portable caddy. Follow every product label and keep chemicals in their original
    containers. Do not mix products or decant them into food or drink containers.
  </p>
  <p>
    Children and pets change the storage decision. If the cupboard cannot provide the control a
    product requires, store it in a more appropriate location. Food, medicines, paper goods,
    electrical items and moisture-sensitive supplies generally need another home.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose storage around the awkward zone</h2>
  <p>
    A low tray can contain minor drips and make bottles easier to remove. A caddy suits products
    carried to another task. Narrow drawers may use space beside pipes, while a simple shelf can
    create a second level where height allows.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check loaded stability, cleaning access and whether the product blocks plumbing. A clever
    multi-level system is not useful if it must be dismantled to inspect a hose.
  </p>

  <h2>Let the bin keep its full working space</h2>
  <p>
    Measure the bin with its lid open and the liner being removed. Leave room for the hand to lift
    it without catching a shelf or pipe. A second waste stream only belongs there if both bins can
    be used and cleaned without crowding the doors.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not force bottles into the narrow space behind a bin where they cannot be seen or retrieved.
    If the bin consumes the cabinet, that may simply be the cabinet's main job.
  </p>

  <h2>Use surfaces that reveal spills</h2>
  <p>
    Smooth, removable and wipeable trays make residue and leaks visible. Avoid materials that
    absorb liquid, trap moisture or conceal the cabinet base. Raised storage can help with minor
    splash exposure, but it must remain stable and easy to clean beneath.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep daily items in the front row</h2>
  <p>
    Dishwashing liquid, the current cleaner or a small caddy should be reachable without shifting
    refills. Move bulk supplies and rarely used products to suitable controlled storage elsewhere.
    Fewer bottles also make changes in the cabinet easier to notice.
  </p>

  <h2>Use rental-friendly products without assuming no risk</h2>
  <p>
    Freestanding trays and caddies usually avoid altering the cabinet. Adhesive, tension or
    mounted products still require checks against the lease, finish and instructions. Do not
    attach storage where it blocks services or could damage a damp or ageing surface.
  </p>
  <p>
    The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/renter-friendly-kitchen-storage-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">renter-friendly kitchen guide</a>{" "}
    covers surface and approval questions across the room.
  </p>

  <h2>Where under-sink storage goes wrong</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>An organiser hides a leak, valve or service point.</li>
    <li>Measurements ignore pipe depth, hinges or the door opening.</li>
    <li>A bin cannot open or lift out when the storage is full.</li>
    <li>Absorbent baskets trap residue and moisture.</li>
    <li>Hazardous products remain accessible to children or pets.</li>
    <li>Food, medicines or electrical items are stored in an unsuitable damp zone.</li>
    <li>Bulk refills crowd out the few products used each day.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to note before choosing anything</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Internal width, depth and height around every pipe and fitting.</li>
    <li>The narrowest door opening and hinge sweep.</li>
    <li>Required plumbing inspection and service access.</li>
    <li>Bin footprint with its lid open and liner being removed.</li>
    <li>The height and label requirements of products that may stay.</li>
    <li>Child, pet, spill, cleaning and rental controls.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Under-sink storage works when the cabinet stays easy to inspect and the correct daily items
    are easy to reach. Empty space around plumbing is not wasted space; it is access.
  </p>
  <p>
    If unrelated overflow is creating the pressure, solve it at the source: use the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/pantry-storage-what-to-measure-before-buying-organisers/">pantry guide</a>{" "}
    for food, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/kitchen-drawer-storage-what-to-measure-before-buying-organisers/">drawer guide</a>{" "}
    for small tools and the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/small-kitchen-appliances-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">appliance guide</a>{" "}
    for equipment that needs a suitable dry home.
  </p>

